01","1179–1210":"1179–1210","1181–Male":"1181–Overleden","1183–Female":"1183–Overleden","1129–1167":"1129–1167","1131–1170":"1131–1170","1154":"1154","1131":"1131","1183":"1183","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1181":"1181","1129":"1129","1179":"1179","1201":"1201","1157":"1157","1167":"1167","1178":"1178","1155":"1155","1210":"1210","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Leicester, Leicestershire, England":"Leicester, Leicestershire, England"},"en":{"1155–1193":"1155–1193","1157–Male":"1157–Deceased","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","1160–1201":"1160–1201","1179–1210":"1179–1210","1181–Male":"1181–Deceased","1183–Female":"1183–Deceased","1129–1167":"1129–1167","1131–1170":"1131–1170","1154":"1154","1131":"1131","1183":"1183","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1181":"1181","1129":"1129","1179":"1179","1201":"1201","1157":"1157","1167":"1167","1178":"1178","1155":"1155","1210":"1210","Leicestershire, England":"Leicestershire, England","Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Leicester, Leicestershire, England":"Leicester, Leicestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cooke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Cook  .","History: Francis Cooke (died 1663) and his eldest son John were passengers on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1621; they were joined two years later by Francis's wife and other children. In the words of William Bradford, he lived long enough ‘to see his children's children have children’."],"variants":[{"name":"Cook","meanings":["English: occupational name for a cook, a seller of cooked meats, or a keeper of an eating house, from Middle English <i>cok</i>, <i>coke</i>, <i>cook</i>, <i>couk</i>, <i>cuk(e)</i> (Old English <i>cōc</i>) ‘cook’ or ‘seller of cooked foods’. See also   Kew  .","Irish and Scottish: usually identical in origin with the English name (see 1 above), but in some cases a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cúg</b> ‘son of Hugo’ (see   McCook  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘cook’, such as German and Jewish   Koch  , Dutch   Kook  , Polish <b>Kucharz</b> and   Kucharczyk  , Slovenian and Croatian   Kuhar  , North German   Kuk  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Cooke was born in 1155, in Leicester, Leicestershire, England, his father, Sir Abraham Cooke, was 26 and his mother, Margaret Greene, was 24. He married Jane Aurcomb in 1178, in Leicestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1193, in his hometown, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1155–1193":"1155–1193","1157–Male":"1157–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1160–1201":"1160–1201","1179–1210":"1179–1210","1181–Male":"1181–Surnud","1183–Female":"1183–Surnud","1129–1167":"1129–1167","1131–1170":"1131–1170","1154":"1154","1131":"1131","1183":"1183","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1181":"1181","1129":"1129","1179":"1179","1201":"1201","1157":"1157","1167":"1167","1178":"1178","1155":"1155